This is the 5th beta release (4.99e) of what will eventually become
the PLPLOT 5.0 distribution.  At this point I'm mainly trying to root out the
remaining bugs and system dependencies, but there will undoubtably be a
few improvements yet before the final version sees the light of day.

Please refer to the following files for more information:

README		General introduction, where to get more information, etc.
README.1st	This file
Changes.log	Log of changes to plplot in reverse chronological order.
ToDo		Describes what's on the agenda (no promises, however :-).

Also there is system-specific documentation under sys/<system-name>, and
a PLPLOT manual in the doc directory (not necessarily up-to-date, however).

For more detail of these changes, consult Changes.log.

**************************************************************************
Version 4.99e: Summary of major changes (bug fix update only)
**************************************************************************

o Added explicit support for Ultrix and Convex systems.  Modified
m4 config files, configure, and header files appropriately.

o Header file prototype sections completely reworked.  Now each prototype
taken directly from the definition (so includes variable names) and is
accompanied by a brief description of what the function does.  This makes
the header file much more useful as a quick reminder of the argument
syntax for each function (i.e. a poor man's manual).

o Changed the minimum distance a grid line must be from the boundary in
order for it to be drawn.  

o The user can now specify an exit handler for plplot via the plsexit()
function.  The old mechanism where a custom pl_exit is supplied does not
work on all systems and is no longer supported.

o The plflush() function now calls a driver-specific flush if the driver
requests this capability.  So the X driver now tells the X server to flush
and the TK driver flushes its FIFO when the user calls plflush(),
resulting in the page being completely drawn.

o Metafiles are now created with the number of pages stored near the head
of the file.  At each new page, a seek is made back to the beginning for
it to be updated.  plrender uses this information to enable seeks backward
from the end of the file.  To do this simply specify "--" and then the
number of pages backward.  Can be used as argument to one of the
page-specifying arguments (-b, -e, -p) or when interactively seeking
("--<n><CR>").  Only works for newly created metafiles!

o TK driver updated to work with Tcl7.1/TK3.4 and later (actually tested
with Tcl7.2/TK3.5; I skipped the 7.1/3.4 release).  TK driver now
eliminates dangerous Tcl commands by renaming them!  I had forgotten to do
this previously (only did so for plserver's Tcl interpreter).  A tricks
and tips file named "Xauthority" was added to the doc directory.

o error in bounding box for PS driver fixed

o stubs and definitions fixed for PLSCOLBG, PLEOP, PLBOP.  Should be OK
to use from Fortran now.


**************************************************************************
Version 4.99d: Summary of major changes (major update!)
**************************************************************************

NOTE: I moved the old Changes.log to the doc directory -- I may need to
reference it when I eventually update the docs, but is otherwise of
questionable relevance.  Also, for some more notes on the current package
see "doc/notes4.99d".

o A fully interactive driver based on the X-windows Tcl/TK toolkit
developed.  Supports zooms, scrolling, page layout, orientation, printing
current plot, all from a menu.  Help menu entries also available, as well
as forward/backward page button (only plrender has the backward page
button) and end of plot indicator.  Colors and fonts are
user-customizable.  Entire layout designed to be user-customizable
although this aspect has not been well tested.  

You can get the Tcl/TK package by anonymous ftp from sprite.berkeley.edu
in the tcl subdirectory (or from harbor.ecn.purdue.edu in directory
pub/tcl).  Also consult with the comp.lang.tcl newsgroup on Usenet.  The
most recent version is Tcl 7.0 and TK 3.3, and if you are just starting
out make sure to get that.  The previous release was Tcl 6.7 and TK 3.2,
and the plplot/TK driver will work with that as well.  Note: to build, you
need to have the Tcl/TK header files where they can be found by the C
compiler (/usr/local/include is a good place).  The Tcl/TK package uses
"xauth" style security in order to make using it a bit safer (against
hacking).  There are some notes on setting this up in the file Xauthority
in the doc directory.

o Changed all plplot source files to include plplotP.h (private) rather
than plplot.h.  Rationalized namespace -- all externally-visible plplot
functions now start with "pl"; device driver functions start with "plD_".

o Several driver functions consolidated, for all drivers.  The width and
color commands are now part of a more general "state" command.  The text
and graph commands used for switching between modes is now handled by the
escape function (very few drivers require it).  The device-specific PLDev
structure is now malloc'ed for each driver that requires it, and freed
when the stream is terminated.  Eliminated low-level coordinate scaling;
now done by driver interface.

o Went wild with "const correctness".  Can now pass a C++ String type to
most (all that I know of) PLPLOT functions.  This works b/c String has an
implicit conversion to const char *.  Now that PLPLOT routines take const
char * rather than char *, use from C++ is much easier.  (contributed by
Geoff Furnish)

o Added search of INSTALL_DIR for font files, passed in from makefile.
Directories now can be specified without the trailing slash, and the path
name is built up correctly (I hope) on Unix, Amiga, and MS-DOS (so special
handling for passing strings with a trailing backslash is gone).

o Created a Driver interface layer.  This sits between the PLPLOT main
source code and the drivers, and is responsible for any user-specified
transformations, including: orientation, page layout, plot view (for
zooming), and transformations (to plot to a different device than
originally intended, used for page dumps).  Thus, orientation, page
layout, etc is now supported with ALL drivers, because it is done in the
driver interface.  Many utility functions added for support of an
interactive windowing driver, currently used by the Tcl/TK driver.

o The option table now requires passing of a pointer to user-defined data,
similar in spirit to that used in Xt or TK callbacks.  If unused, simply
initialize as NULL.  All option handlers changed to accept this pointer as
the third argument.  Especially useful from C++ for passing the "this"
pointer.  The flags -mar, -a, -jx, -jy for setting margin, aspect ratio,
and justification, -wplt for changing the plot window, and -ori to set the
orientation are now handled by the plplot command line handler.  These
call functions in the driver interface layer to do the appropriate
transformation.  Modified -bg argument handler to strip leading '#' off
hex color value if present, to allow it to deal with TCL-style color
values.  Added support for -nopixmap option.

o Fill algorithm improved and simplified.  New shading routine plshade,
arrow draw routine plarrows.  Contributed by Wesley Ebisuzaki.

o Changed all names that ended with an underscore (as part of the
C/Fortran linkage) to end with a '7' instead, to avoid problems with f2c.

o X driver: Added escape function to redraw plot (unlike resize, the
window size remains unchanged).  Changed draw functions to only draw to
the pixmap during page redraws.  Pixmap is then copied to the actual
window when done, for faster and more smooth response.  Added error
handler to trap pixmap allocation errors, and switch to a slower method
(redraw) of refreshing window on exposes.

o Tek driver: Merged with xterm code, and added code to handle Tektronix
4105/4107 (color) devices.  For now just the color index selection is
supported.  Added code to change terminal line to noncanonical (cbreak)
mode on POSIX systems so that entered keystrokes (including <Backspace>
and "Q" from plrender) do not require a <CR> to be recognized.

o MGR and VGA drivers for use under Linux contributed by Sergio
Fanchiotti.

o Fixes and driver for DOS/Borland environment contributed by Paul
Casteels (casteels@uia.ac.be).

o Changed method for getting stub conversion right.  Now need to define
the macro STUB_LINKAGE with any of the supported conversion types.  Moved
determination of stub name handling to plstubs.h.

o New systems supported: IRIX, DEC Alpha-based machines running OSF/1,
NEC SX-3.

o plrender changes: Updated to work with new command option handler.
Fixed several bugs in page seeking code.  Removed code that is now handled
in the driver interface, also made changes to reflect new driver functions.

o Archiver scripts renamed as follows:

tarup	Archive scripts.  Renamed to be more generic.  Updated to work
zipup	with current file organization.
zooup

o Build mechanism changed substantially.  Master makefile.m4 now split
into a number of different utility m4 files.  Makes addition of new
systems a snap.  A /bin/sh configure script is now use for building
plplot, allowing automatic determination of system type and other
niceties.  To build package, cd to tmp directory and type "../configure",
then "make".  See the README file in the m4 directory for more info,
also the appropriate system specific README file.

o Note: DOS and OS/2 drivers not updated and most certainly are broken
now.  I need someone to support these platforms as the original DOS &
OS/2 developers have switched to Linux.

